BOOK V.

THE funeral games in this book make an agreeable interlude in the more serious action of the poem. Many of the incidents of these games are taken directly from the account of the funeral games of Patroclus in the twenty-third book of the Iliad. The contest of ships, however, and the equestrian exhibition‚ are features wholly original. The incident of the burning of the fleet, variously told, was part os the old Trojan legend.
